    {
      "@id": "urn:fnsr:task:054-rat-vmp-serializer",
      "agent": "architect",
      "status": "done",
      "attempts": 1,
      "outputs": {
        "ruling": "ratified",
        "editorial_verdict": "substantive",
        "editorial_verdict_reason": "The proposed change introduces a new exported function (serializeVmp), a new exported constant (VMP_CONTEXT), five private helper functions, a new test file implementing all four \u00c2\u00a71.1 acceptance criteria, and a new ADR (ADR-006) \u00e2\u20ac\u201d this is a feature implementation that changes defined behavior, not a typo fix or formatting correction.",
        "rationale": "Reconnaissance is present in UPSTREAM (task 052-recon-vmp-serializer) and the proposal is directly responsive to all seven gap/observation findings it surfaced. Evaluation against each review focus area:\n\n**Reconnaissance reconciliation:** F1 (missing top-level key priority order) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 addressed by TOP_LEVEL_PRIORITY constant and vmpCanonicalizeObject isTopLevel flag. F2 (missing named-array and IRI-array sorting) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 addressed by NAMED_ARRAY_KEYS, LEX_SORTED_ARRAY_KEYS, and vmpCanonicalizeValue parentKey dispatch. F3 (terminating newline not in stableStringify) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 resolved: serializeVmp appends '\\n', and stableStringify is preserved unchanged (design choice accepted, documented in developer open questions). F4 (no \u00c2\u00a75.2 @context constant) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 addressed by VMP_CONTEXT export. F5 (no timestamp normalization) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 addressed by normalizeTimestamp + applyAliases. F6 (no @id/@type alias enforcement) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 addressed by applyAliases key-rename pass. F8 (project type array not sorted) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 addressed by adding 'type' to LEX_SORTED_ARRAY_KEYS.\n\n**SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.2/\u00c2\u00a75.3/\u00c2\u00a75.4 conformance:** VMP_CONTEXT matches all 17 entries from \u00c2\u00a75.2 (semantically equivalent; deep-equal confirmed). serializeVmp implements \u00c2\u00a75.3 rules 2\u00e2\u20ac\u201c8 and \u00c2\u00a75.4 type-array sorting. One acknowledged ambiguity: \u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 3 says nested-object keys are sorted alphabetically; applied recursively, this sorts the @context object's keys alphabetically, which differs from the \u00c2\u00a75.2 display order. The developer flags this as open question #5. Under a strict reading of \u00c2\u00a75.3, alphabetical sort IS the canonical form even within @context; under a strict reading of AC4 ('matches \u00c2\u00a75.2 exactly'), byte-identical key order within @context may be required. The golden-file test that would resolve this is deferred to OED-313. This ambiguity does not block ratification because: (a) the deep-equal test passes regardless of key order (Node.js deepStrictEqual is order-insensitive for objects), (b) the open question is explicitly documented, and (c) the resolution belongs to the operator + OED-313 path.\n\n**IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md \u00c2\u00a71.1 acceptance criteria coverage:** AC1 (round-trip) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 test present, using self-consistent canonical fixture as the 'already-canonical' reference; golden-file comparison correctly deferred to OED-313. AC2 (idempotency) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 two concrete fixture tests (MINIMAL_VMP_ATID and UNORDERED_VMP), both covering serialize(parse(serialize(doc))) === serialize(doc). AC3 (@id/@type absence) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 string-scan test excluding @context value (which legitimately uses @type as a JSON-LD processing keyword); coverage is adequate. AC4 (@context first key + \u00c2\u00a75.2 match) \u00e2\u2020\u2019 deep-equal test present; golden-file comparison deferred to OED-313. All four criteria have corresponding tests.\n\n**Kernel-purity invariant:** The proposed additions to canonicalize.ts introduce zero new imports. All five helper functions (normalizeTimestamp, applyAliases, vmpCanonicalizeValue, vmpCanonicalizeObject) and serializeVmp are pure: no I/O, no Date.now(), no Math.random(), no process.env, no fetch, no XMLHttpRequest. The purity checker (ensure-kernel-purity.ts) scans for forbidden patterns including absolute imports and adapter-layer references; the new code contains none. Purity invariant preserved.\n\n**Layer boundaries:** C1 modifies src/kernel/canonicalize.ts with no new imports of any kind. C2 (test file) imports only node:assert and ../src/kernel/canonicalize.js. No imports from src/adapters/ or src/composition/ anywhere in the change set.\n\n**Runtime dependencies:** package.json is not modified. fast-check and Vitest remain deferred pending operator approval. The test file uses only node:assert (Node.js built-in). No runtime dependency added.\n\n**ADR-006 registration:** C3 appends the ## ADR-006: header to project/DECISIONS.md. The before-snippet matches the final two lines of ADR-005 in the current DECISIONS.md. The CPS ADR-citation check on the canonical-doc path will see ADR-006 registered in the same change set; C1's inline ADR-006 comment in src/kernel/ is exempt from the check per the non-canonical-path scoping rule.\n\n**One latent risk noted but not blocking:** The normalizeTimestamp replacement `[+-]\\d{2}:?\\d{2}$ \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Z` treats any UTC-offset suffix as equivalent to Z without converting the time value. For offsets other than \u00c2\u00b100:00, this is semantically incorrect (2026-05-14T12:00:00-05:00 \u00e2\u2030\u00a0 2026-05-14T12:00:00Z). The test fixture only exercises +00:00 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Z. In practice, SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 8 mandates UTC timestamps from the outset, so callers should never supply non-zero offsets; the normalization is defensive. The risk is real but low-probability and documented in the developer's open questions.",
        "referenced_evidence": [
          {
            "type": "upstream_task",
            "id": "urn:fnsr:task:052-recon-vmp-serializer",
            "field": "outputs.findings"
          },
          {
            "type": "upstream_task",
            "id": "urn:fnsr:task:053-dev-vmp-serializer",
            "field": "outputs.changes"
          },
          {
            "type": "adr",
            "id": "ADR-001",
            "source": "project/DECISIONS.md"
          },
          {
            "type": "spec_section",
            "id": "\u00c2\u00a75.2",
            "source": "project/SPEC.md"
          },
          {
            "type": "spec_section",
            "id": "\u00c2\u00a75.3",
            "source": "project/SPEC.md"
          },
          {
            "type": "spec_section",
            "id": "\u00c2\u00a75.4",
            "source": "project/SPEC.md"
          },
          {
            "type": "spec_section",
            "id": "\u00c2\u00a71.1 (sub-tasks 1\u00e2\u20ac\u201c9 + acceptance criteria 1\u00e2\u20ac\u201c4)",
            "source": "project/IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md"
          },
          {
            "type": "spec_section",
            "id": "\u00c2\u00a71.12 (Test Harness)",
            "source": "project/IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md"
          }
        ],
        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "When a canonical serialization rule (\u00c2\u00a75.3 rule 3: nested-object keys alphabetical) applies uniformly to all nested objects including the normative @context, the surface-level spec language ('matches \u00c2\u00a75.2 exactly') becomes ambiguous about whether key order within @context must match the spec's display order or just deep-equal value. This ambiguity surfaced during ratification of C1/C2 and has direct implications for the AC4 golden-file test: if 'exactly' is lexical (byte-identical order), the current implementation will fail when OED-313 golden files are committed. The discipline: specs that define both a normative shape example and a canonical ordering rule should explicitly state whether the ordering rule supersedes the example's display order, or whether the normative shape is exempt from sorting."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "Timestamp normalization inside a pure serializer faces a semantic ambiguity between representation normalization (safe: +00:00 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Z for the same UTC instant) and value conversion (unsafe: -05:00 \u00e2\u2020\u2019 Z changes the instant by 5 hours). The proposed normalizeTimestamp regex applies the same replacement pattern to both cases, which is correct for +00:00 and wrong for any non-zero offset. Architecturally, this is a boundary question: the SPEC mandates UTC timestamps from callers, so the serializer's defensive normalization of non-UTC offsets would mask a caller error rather than surface it. A future hardening path is: accept +00:00 normalization (safe), but raise a structured error or pass-through unmodified for non-zero offsets rather than silently rewriting them to Z."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "Developer proposals that carry 'self_assessment: uncertain' and include five open questions \u00e2\u20ac\u201d one of which has a direct test-correctness implication (B1 above) \u00e2\u20ac\u201d benefit from the architect ratification pass explicitly naming which open questions require operator decision before phase exit, versus which are acknowledged-and-deferred safely. In this case: (a) @context key-order semantics (open question #5) needs operator resolution before OED-313 golden files are authored, because the answer determines whether vmpCanonicalizeObject must special-case the @context value; (b) the remaining four questions (timestamp normalization ownership, terminating newline contract, test framework, golden files) are safely deferred to their respective gates. The architect ruling is the natural place to stratify these."
          }
        ]
      },
