        "open_questions": [
          "FIELD COUNT MISMATCH (reconnaissance F2/F3): SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.15 Required: line enumerates 7 fields (id, type, ecm:format, ecm:filename, ecm:contentHash, ecm:generatedAt, ecm:isSerializationOf). IMPL plan \u00c2\u00a71.8 sub-tasks enumerate 8 (adds ecm:byteLength). IMPL plan \u00c2\u00a71.8 AC1 says 'six'. This proposal implements 8 fields (7 SPEC Required + ecm:byteLength) per the sub-tasks enumeration; the AC1 count of 'six' appears to be a typo. Operator should confirm the authoritative field set and correct the IMPL plan AC1 wording if 8 is the intent.",
          "MERMAID MIME TYPE: SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.15 line 664 says 'text/x-mermaid (or text/plain if no registered type)'. This proposal passes format through from ArtifactInput.format \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the caller decides the MIME value. Operator or a future task should document which value the CLI emits for Mermaid artifacts.",
          "DETERMINISM for ecm:uuid-urn entry IDs: each SerializationEntry id is a new UUIDv4 (non-deterministic per SPEC \u00c2\u00a79.2 acknowledgment). If replay-determinism for manifest entries is ever required, the entry IDs would need to switch to ecm:deterministic mode or be supplied by the caller. Not a blocker for Phase 1 task 1.8, but worth recording as a forward-track.",
          "ONTOLOGY TOUCH: no .owl/.ttl/.jsonld/.schema.json files are modified by this proposal. No semantic-sme review required for this change."
        ],
        "summary": "Proposes two new files: (C1) src/manifest/index.ts \u00e2\u20ac\u201d the generateManifestEntries implementation exporting ArtifactInput and SerializationEntry interfaces; (C2) tests/manifest-entries.test.ts \u00e2\u20ac\u201d hand-rolled test suite covering IMPL plan \u00c2\u00a71.8 AC1\u00e2\u20ac\u201cAC4. The source uses createHash('sha256') following the established src/iri/index.ts pattern, generateIri('ecm:uuid-urn',{}) for entry IDs, and derives both ecm:contentHash and ecm:byteLength by normalizing contentBytes to Buffer. The test independently computes the expected SHA-256 for a known string and compares, tests multi-byte UTF-8 byte counting with caf\\u00e9 (5 bytes for 4 chars), and guards the project.id runtime validation. No existing files are modified; no new runtime dependencies; layer boundaries preserved.",
