          {
            "id": "F20",
            "claim": "The `makeInfo()` helper already exists in `src/validate/index.ts` at lines 90\u00e2\u20ac\u201c103 and can emit the NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE finding using the same code path as LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER, requiring only an import of `NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE` from codes.ts and a conditional check for the marker field.",
            "evidence": [
              {
                "file": "src/validate/index.ts",
                "lines": "90-103",
                "excerpt": "function makeInfo(\n  code: string,\n  message: string,\n  target: string,\n): ValidationFinding { ... }"
              },
              {
                "file": "src/validate/index.ts",
                "lines": "12-16",
                "excerpt": "import {\n  MISSING_REALIST_ANCHOR,\n  INVALID_SPEC_VERSION,\n  LEGACY_REALIST_ANCHOR_PLACEHOLDER,\n} from \"./codes.js\";"
              }
            ],
            "kind": "inference"
          }
        ],
        "summary": "Task 1.10 (Canonical Normalization on Load) is fully specified in IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md \u00c2\u00a71.10 and grounded in SPEC.md \u00c2\u00a75.3 / FR-C014. The implementation requires: (1) a new module `src/normalize/index.ts` (directory does not yet exist) exporting `normalizeOnLoad(doc): {document, wasNormalized}`; (2) a one-line import addition and a marker-conditional `makeInfo()` call in `src/validate/index.ts` to emit the `NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE` info finding; and (3) a new `tests/normalize-on-load.test.ts` covering the three acceptance criteria. The code infrastructure is well-prepared: `serializeVmp` is fully implemented and idempotent, `NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE` is already declared in codes.ts, the `makeInfo()` helper exists in validate/index.ts, and the marker-field pattern (analogous to `ecm:_legacyAnchorPlaceholder`) is the established precedent from task 1.9. The primary open question is the mechanism for byte comparison: the IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN states 'bytewise' but the function receives a parsed JS object (not the original file string), so true byte-level comparison against the file on disk is not possible from the function signature alone. In practice, the check would compare `serializeVmp(doc)` against `JSON.stringify(doc, null, 2) + '\\n'` \u00e2\u20ac\u201d which detects structural non-canonicality (key ordering, array ordering, timestamp format) but not encoding-level differences (BOM, CRLF). The Phase 2 task 2.1 call chain confirms `normalizeOnLoad` receives a parsed JS object (migrate() output), not a raw file string.",
        "evidence_paths": [
          "project/SPEC.md",
          "project/IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md",
          "phase1-task-1-10-chain.json",
          "src/kernel/canonicalize.ts",
