      "@id": "urn:fnsr:task:140-rat-normalize-on-load",
      "agent": "architect",
      "status": "done",
      "attempts": 1,
      "outputs": {
        "ruling": "ratified",
        "editorial_verdict": "substantive",
        "editorial_verdict_reason": "The proposed change introduces a new module (src/normalize/index.ts), modifies a validator to emit a new finding code, and adds a new test file \u00e2\u20ac\u201d this is a feature implementation, not a typo, formatting, or terminology-tightening correction.",
        "rationale": "Reconnaissance (urn:fnsr:task:138-recon-normalize-on-load) is present in UPSTREAM and provides sufficient grounding. All four review-focus areas pass evaluation:\n\n1. SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.3 / FR-C014 CONFORMANCE: SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.3 (lines 338\u00e2\u20ac\u201c339) defines the normalization-on-load trigger; FR-C014 (line 1314) binds it as a functional requirement. The implementation satisfies both: normalizeOnLoad detects non-canonical structure (key order, array sort order, timestamp format, missing @context) and returns the canonical form. The limitation that BOM/CRLF encoding-level differences in the original file cannot be detected from a parsed-object input is documented in the developer's open_questions and is structurally unavoidable given the Phase 2 call chain (FR-U002: migrate() + normalizeOnLoad() + validate() \u00e2\u20ac\u201d normalizeOnLoad receives a parsed JS object, not raw bytes). IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN \u00c2\u00a71.10's 'bytewise from input' language is correctly interpreted as 'structural comparison on the parsed representation'.\n\n2. ALL THREE ACs COVERED: AC1 (idempotency) is exercised by both the second-call-on-normalized-doc path and the CANONICAL_DOC path in C4. AC2 (non-canonical fixture returns wasNormalized: true) uses NON_CANONICAL_DOC with reversed type array, wrong iao:isAbout order, and no @context \u00e2\u20ac\u201d confirmed detectable by the serializeVmp-vs-JSON.stringify comparison. AC3 (NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE iff wasNormalized) is exercised by both the true path (normalizeOnLoad(NON_CANONICAL_DOC) + validate) and the false path (normalizeOnLoad(CANONICAL_DOC) + validate) in C4. The test correctly checks ecm:severity: 'ecm:info' and ecm:acknowledged: false against the SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.13 / \u00c2\u00a717.4 schema.\n\n3. VALIDATOR MARKER MECHANISM: The ecm:_wasNormalizedOnLoad pattern directly parallels the ecm:_legacyAnchorPlaceholder precedent from task 1.9 (src/migrate/index.ts line 204 / src/validate/index.ts lines 142\u00e2\u20ac\u201c143). The marker is stripped from docForComparison before the canonicality comparison, which correctly guarantees idempotency on the second call. The C2/C3 before-snippets for src/validate/index.ts match the current file exactly (lines 12\u00e2\u20ac\u201c16 and lines 189\u00e2\u20ac\u201c211 verified). The NORMALIZED_ON_SAVE constant is already declared in src/validate/codes.ts line 54; C2 wires the import; C3 adds the conditional makeInfo() call before the return statement, removing the now-resolved task-1.10 TODO comment. Layer boundary is respected throughout: src/normalize/index.ts imports only from ../kernel/canonicalize.js; no imports from src/adapters/ or src/composition/; pure function contract maintained.\n\n4. SUBSTANTIVE VERDICT: The change implements a new spec-required feature (SPEC \u00c2\u00a75.3 / FR-C014) with a new module, a validator extension, and test coverage. It is squarely substantive. The architectural approach \u00e2\u20ac\u201d parsed-object canonicality detection via serializeVmp comparison, marker-field bridge to validate(), idempotency via marker-stripping-before-comparison \u00e2\u20ac\u201d is structurally sound and consistent with established project patterns.\n\nOne minor open item acknowledged: src/normalize/ is not enumerated as a named layer in docs/ARCHITECTURE.md. The developer calls this out as a follow-up editorial change. The module behaves as a pure Layer-0-adjacent function (no I/O, no restricted imports, same behavioral contract as src/validate/ and src/migrate/). This gap does not block the feature but should be addressed in a follow-up.",
        "referenced_evidence": [
          {
