          }
        ],
        "bankings": [
          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The 'marker field on document bridges pre-processing context to pure validator without changing function signature' pattern has now been applied twice in this codebase: ecm:_legacyAnchorPlaceholder (task 1.9, src/migrate/index.ts \u00e2\u2020\u2019 src/validate/index.ts) and ecm:_wasNormalizedOnLoad (task 1.10, src/normalize/index.ts \u00e2\u2020\u2019 src/validate/index.ts). Both use the same structural shape: the pre-processing step sets a boolean marker on the document object, validate() reads the marker to select which finding to emit, and the marker is an ecm:-prefixed key with an underscore-prefixed name to signal implementation-internal status. This pattern is now a confirmed project-level convention for passing load-path context to a pure validator without breaking the pure-function signature or adding optional parameters."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN language describing operations at a higher abstraction level than the actual implementation interface creates interpretation gaps when implementations arrive. Here, \u00c2\u00a71.10 specified 'bytewise from input' while the function signature accepts a parsed JS object, making true byte-level comparison impossible. The resolution \u00e2\u20ac\u201d 'bytewise' resolved as 'structural comparison on the parsed representation, consistent with the Phase 2 call chain' \u00e2\u20ac\u201d was sound, but required explicit developer acknowledgment and open_question surfacing during reconnaissance. Future IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN sub-task authoring should align operation descriptions with the concrete interface level (e.g., 'compare serializeVmp output against JSON.stringify of the input object') or explicitly note the abstraction-level mismatch and the resolution strategy."
          }
        ]
      },
