          {
            "id": "B1",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "OED resolution traces live in chain.json focus_areas annotations but not in the IMPL PLAN OED gate list or the ADR body. In this chain, OED-307's closure was confirmed only because phase1-task-1-11-chain.json line 17 annotated 'OED-307 resolved: ...' inline. The IMPL PLAN OED gate entry and ADR-003 do not cross-reference each other. Future reconnaissance tasks for IMPL PLAN tasks whose \u00c2\u00a7N.N SPEC refs include an OED should treat OED status as a named output field ('oed_gate_status': {id, resolved_by, open}) rather than a finding that may or may not surface depending on how the recon agent traverses evidence."
          },
          {
            "id": "B2",
            "category": "methodology-refinement-candidate",
            "content": "ADR-003 broadened exit code 2 to cover three meanings (file I/O error, path containment escape, not-yet-implemented stub) without scheduling a follow-up editorial-correction to SPEC \u00c2\u00a723, which still lists exit 2 as 'file I/O errors' only. This creates a persistent gap between normative spec text and ADR-ratified behavior that every future agent reading SPEC \u00c2\u00a723 will encounter. The discipline candidate: every ADR that redefines or broadens a normative-spec-defined named constant (exit code, error code, enumeration value) should include in its consequences list a forward-reference to a pending editorial-correction chain to update the spec text. This makes the spec\u00e2\u2020\u2019ADR divergence a tracked obligation rather than an implicit follow-up."
          },
          {
            "id": "B3",
            "category": "pattern-observation",
            "content": "The developer's 'self_assessment: uncertain' with TypeScript compilation unknowns explicitly enumerated in open_questions (parseArgs return-type inference, definite-assignment through never-returning process.exit() calls) is a healthy signal discipline for agent-authored code changes that touch type-inference boundaries. Rather than asserting compilation success, the developer identified the two specific failure modes and provided mitigation directions. This pattern reduces operator surprise at build-verification time and is preferable to confident assertions that prove false at npm run build. Worth reinforcing as a norm for developer agents when a change touches TypeScript inference-sensitive code paths."
          }
        ]
